GeneralNote: Holten et al. (1989:5) say: "Eurah is a thick bush, with red flowers and long thin leaves. We used it to kill germs and to heal skin diseases like boils, rash, itch, school sores, scabies. We stripped the leaves from the branches; we put a lot of these leaves into a kerosene tin with water and boiled it over the fire. The water went a greeny brown colour. We used this liquid for healing skin diseases. Sometimes we would pour a jugful into the bath. The mixture had to be strong (more eurah than water). Most families had a kerosene tin of eurah by the fire; we left it to boil over the fire for many days, and the mixture became very strong".

For the present it is recommended that winanga-y be used to translate these, since it is the form that is used slightly more often in the sources. The English words â€˜rememberâ€™ and â€˜understandâ€™ are overwhelmingly or exclusively translated by winanga-y.
